BETTER PRACTICE BEFORE DESTROY

Before:

terraform destroy

you should FIRST delete Kubernetes services manually:

kubectl delete svc my-app-service

OR BETTER STILL 

kubectl delete svc --all

Then wait a few minutes.

NOTE : Cleaning Elb and the whole setup will take time.  so the above method help to delete the loadbalancer service first manually using the kubernetes network which is ususally faster and helps save some time

Then run:

terraform destroy

You will run into an error "prevent_destroy set"

which blocks destruction of the EBS volume"  because we enforced 

Recommended for Learning/Lab Environment

Temporarily remove prevent_destroy.

Find this resource in your Jenkins module:

resource "aws_ebs_volume" "jenkins_data" {

You’ll see something like:

lifecycle {
  prevent_destroy = true
}

Temporarily comment it out:

# lifecycle {
#   prevent_destroy = true
# }

Save file.

Then run:  terraform destroy



IN REAL WORLD SCENARIO 

Keep Jenkins Volume

If you want to preserve Jenkins data:

Use targeted destroy.

Example:

terraform destroy \
-target=module.eks \
-target=module.vpc

This leaves:

Jenkins EBS volume
Jenkins persistence

but destroys:

EKS
networking
Kubernetes infrastructure

